{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656339"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.09,0,0.18,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77064"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11452"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10574"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26522"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77064"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENitric oxide plays a crucial role in penile erection by mediating vasodilation and smooth muscle relaxation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism by which nitric oxide produces penile erection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activates cyclic guanosine monophosphate production","Directly relaxes skeletal muscle","Stimulates testosterone release","Blocks calcium entry into smooth muscle","Inhibits sympathetic nerve activity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is that nitric oxide \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivates cyclic guanosine monophosphate production\u003C/strong\u003E. When released from nerve endings and endothelial cells, nitric oxide diffuses into smooth muscle cells where it activates guanylate cyclase. This enzyme produces cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP), which triggers a cascade leading to smooth muscle relaxation in penile vessels and erectile tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium entry into smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a downstream effect of cGMP, not a direct action of nitric oxide\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly relaxes skeletal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - Penile erection involves smooth muscle, not skeletal muscle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits sympathetic nerve activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Nitric oxide works through local mechanisms, not by altering autonomic nerve activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates testosterone release\u003C/strong\u003E - Nitric oxide does not affect hormone production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pathway is the target of phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors like sildenafil, which enhance erection by preventing the breakdown of cGMP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nitric oxide causes smooth muscle relaxation in penile arteries and corpus cavernosum by increasing cyclic guanosine monophosphate.","Parasympathetic nerve stimulation triggers nitric oxide release from nerve endings and endothelial cells.","Phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors enhance erection by preventing breakdown of cyclic guanosine monophosphate."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62570"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T23:36:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T23:37:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11452"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77064"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:34+10:30"},"relati